            "answer_text": "the definition \u201cdemocratic\u201d is itself very difficult, currently it is beeing used by people with huge media presence to define their friends and enemies. everybody wants to be democratic, but in truth and reality democracy can be almost like dictatorships or truly active. however for a democracy to be truly active and vivd, mane core realities have to be deeply imbeded in the democracy and the society. among many i write some i know out of my personal experience. society needs a common language, or means to understand each other.society needs an educated populationsociety needs a population with work morale.society needs a population that thinks socialist regarding the solution of the problems between each other.society needs a trusted mass media systemsociety needs a trusted financial system with the democratically regulated banking/financial system that serves the democracy.7. society needs basic economic stability for everyone involved in the democracy. such standards are quite huge and the democratic penetration into such a society are thin. for example children or less educated people might completely feel excluded out of that society. especially in young countries like in africa the democratic penetration can quickly be very small. and could look almost like in a medieval election of dukes and counts. which only an extremly small percentage of the population is able to decide and be involved. this way you can question yourself how widespread the circle of the democratically involved people are. for example even the muslim khalifate had its councils that commonly discussed decisions just like parliamentarian democracies do. so regarding this you can choose how you feel about a particular democracy in africa. ",
